  "texts": [
    "The fixed-number approach would be more statistically sound, but requires a number of prompts that grows (linearly) with the number of repeated prompts, quickly rendering it more expensive than the one-per-observation approach where the number of prompts is fixed.",
    "We thus turned to the \"silicon sampling\" approach of generating a single LLM answer for each (possibly duplicated) observation in the ground-truth data.",
    "NTP, on the other hand, is cleaner and significantly cheaper: only one token",
    "is produced to answer the question, and the LLM is prompted only once per distinct socio-demographic profile, directly yielding a probability distribution over all available answers.",
    "Theoretically, by limiting its scope to the next valid token, NTP might also be biased in unexpected directions, e.g."
  ],
